Inflation in Europe declined on food
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is primarily due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price rise in the 13 countries of the eurozone was higher than forecasts, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was registered, the Luxembourg European Community Statistics Office said.
Official forecasts have indicated only 3%, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not decrease the principal interest rate by saying that the decrease in interest, with the growth in raw material prices and the decrease in unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflation spirale.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to an analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "It is necessary to dissuade" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this topic later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain, it rose from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area declined due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain market ratings have increased by 88 percent and soybean price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the global oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation rate will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but in 2009 it will drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the steering rate twice in 2008.
Gallup Indicates Government Crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December, and since 2002, it has now had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Poll Institute) has never previously found such a low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greatest determination of the opposition voters, more than two-thirds (71 percent) support against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Hungarian Democrats Forum) and the SZDSZ (Free Democrats Alliance) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is 2% throughout the population.
On loyal voters some to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1%.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who felt the country's economic situation was particularly serious has never been as high as it is 41 percent, and according to 46 percent complementary, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic perspectives of the spring and last summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population is expecting an aggravation and only one tenth is expecting an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of people surveyed, namely a majority never seen during Gallup’s previous surveys, decided that the prime minister did his work rather badly than well.
13 percent of the surveys have a lot of confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister and 27 percent the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political change is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be treated without change of government.
While after the last October riots, 35 per cent of the surveyed wanted the Government and the Prime Minister to remain in charge, this rate currently accounts for only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) estimates that new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question concerning the intent of vote, 60% of the surveyed respond that they would certainly vote and the 20 percent complementary say that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "next Sunday legislative election," only 55 percent of the surveyed would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate in complementary. According to the current intentions, the result of the referendum would not be doubtful.
74 percent of people would say no to enrollment rights in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation expenses, and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay expenses.
When we only look at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote at the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration rights, consultation fees and stay fees in the hospital.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
Hypermarkets in Budaörs’ commercial triangle maintained the average price increase by 16 percent last year, unlike this year’s VAT rate didn’t increase.
Article by Napi Gazdasag (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs trading triangle, the usual daily Christmas Bag also increased by an average of 16 percent, a significantly higher than a thousand forints increased in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already flyed in major food stores last December, no longer increased brutally compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items bought significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily cart in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded at least 91 forints, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forint.)
The prices of Unicum and living fish remained almost at last year, however, the prices of duck, nut and powder have increased significantly.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but in Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to only 139 forints.
Competition did not decrease the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle contained two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the contained bottle including.
This year, in terms of daily cart, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing the most expensive cart of last year and the most expensive cart of this year, we see a 12 percent difference while the difference between the most expensive cart of last year and the most expensive cart of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased on average by 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not visiblely determine which margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader wrongly calculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to trade intensity.)
Due to the change in VAT rate, the increase in daily cart prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than that of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the most expensive basket value was 1,630 forints higher than last year, and the cheapest prices increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we found a catastrophic price rise, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some primary feeds, the statistical institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, of flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Bag, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they managed to accept the brutal price rise by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy all in quantities, they take long-contained foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails formed at the boxes of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers increased suddenly.
But, according to our information, revenue is less significant in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that not even reach the planned revenue, not only for food but also for sustainable consumption items.
Many Hospitals Make Economy on Disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, primarily caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygiene conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overdriving of medical staff do not help block infections, says the chief doctor at the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also economy on disinfectants
A MRSA infection has been diagnosed long ago at the service of traumatology at the Janos Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The sick was isolated.
In the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured from a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after he had to return there because of an MRSA infection and since, doctors could not make an important operation for him because of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogenic agent have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
It is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogenic agent that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as angines, amygdalites, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily healed.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant antibiotic bacteria that will proliferate quickly in bad hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged poor functioning of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infections or septics, on elderly, small weights or with weakened body.
According to the director doctor of the Janos Hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily hospitals.
The infection with the epidemic should not be confused, we do not find MRSA only, or we do not look for them, Tibor Nyulasi said.
The SA resists antibiotics.
"These sick are isolated, the caregivers put rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for curing them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they have MRSA, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample taking is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favorable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistent pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is manifested mainly in hospitals and senior residences, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA patients.
However, microbiological samples are not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these exams.
Most cases only come to date if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the chief doctor of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the adequate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
It is necessary to make efforts for antibiotic therapy to be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take it into account.
The realization of microbiological samples is even more rare in ambulatory and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many Hospitals Make Economy on Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, put gloves and protective masks, however significant gaps are detected in hospitals as well in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by droplet inhalation and contact, however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the contaminated patient cannot always be isolated.
Furthermore, the rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the sick should be removed from each other at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, savings on disinfectants, lacking nurses, many sick, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable manner or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security boxes, which is why we fight everywhere against this infection.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) is a priority to prevent the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and to prevent hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
Commissioner, author of a deadly accident, was not in a state of drunk
The official findings relating to the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd District were drawn up.
It can be excluded that the Commissioner of the 22nd District, who has resigned from his post since, who has crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunk or stubborn condition, said Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Ministry of the Capital after the relative findings have been established.
The conclusion confirmed the first outcome of the investigation that has already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting on the wheel.
