EUR 400 million additional for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), on Friday signed three agreements with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the financing of Hungarian transport and environmental projects to be achieved from the Cohesion Fund, with a credit agreement of EUR 100 million already signed by the parties, this time the signed contract relates to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The credit agreement of EUR 150 million also relates to the financial funding of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later after the extension of the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract of EUR 50 million for innovation, the state budget will first use this envelope as part of the research and development project to be achieved at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of line 4 of the subway was also addressed.
The parties agreed that they would rediscover the eventual amendment to the initial contract when Hungary has completed the details of subway funding with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the funding of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its credits based on the interest rate related to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment commission.
