Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication by Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, professional meetings will end Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, ministers' negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Sheet that is expected to define efforts to be made after the period of reduction of emissions defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, heavy discussions are being held on this issue between developing countries and developed countries.
The United States also reported that at the moment they did not want to discuss exact figures, although they were ready to sign an agreement on reduction of 25 to 40 percent greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is to see whether developed countries are committed, excluding emission reductions, to provide financial and technological assistance to countries that need it.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors of 16 probably members within the framework of the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, confirms the EU’s ambition to retain its role as an admiral ship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the successful signature of the “After 2012 Agreement”, and it was ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also ready to make their responsibility.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signed by the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all of the 15 EU members of that time took the commitment by 8 per cent increasingly.
Hungary has taken its commitment to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release from the Ministry of Environment.
The issue is big in Bali because the long-term international climate policy agreement must be established within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be repeated after 2012. In this case, Nobel Climate Reduction commitments below the values set out in the UN Kyoto Protocol would not immediately be followed by a new international system of reduction in emissions underlined the international IPCC.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the rise in the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celcius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruit on YouTube
The British army units communicate, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First of all, it was the British Air Force (RAF) who has been passionate about YouTube: the special units speaking in Afghanistan charge video sequences on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the headquarters of the air force operations in Kandahar and then transferred to Londres or the compatriots loading them on the Internet.
The political message is indispensable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this path and their "chain" was watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence enrolled in the spring of 2007 as "defenceheadquarters" and it communicates videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial goal of the air force, the videos were brought on the net to recruit, and according to the Department of Defense, they also served to make the public known the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published by this path costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, reported to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, advisor in defence, but also inevitably carrying a political message as it justifies in a special form the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is embarrassed because, except for composed and carefully censured videos, amateur videos have passed on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocrites, officers don't avoid talking about losses but never present the bloody side of the fight.
Furthermore, many videos had already been brought on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were performed in a real mission, but the British army only packed for loading these videos recently.
The Americans do recruitment a little differently by using the American Army shooting game that can be downloaded for free. In this game, the player can get directly in the place of soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
