The most important of the four claims, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be implemented from next year be introduced in several steps.
The third claim requires a guarantee in terms of retirement before legal age, which would allow the functions that deserve it to pass into the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ), linked to the League Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economic and Transportation relating to secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increased Country Risk
According to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyaroszágért Mozgalom (Movement for Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its “risk warning,” the society reports that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the biggest political risk is that “short-term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur following the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Zigan population and not Zigan population of Hungary.”
The research institute added that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard to probably cause this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main gaps of Hungarian political actors: “The public actors have passed the public debate on the matter of the Roma to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Zigans and the Hungarians.”
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, the activity of the Hungarian Guard “deteriorated significantly the image of Hungary abroad, especially regarding confidence in the country’s stability and democratic maturity.”
They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been established in Hungary since the summer of 2007 called the "National Self-Defense Association".
“The common characteristic of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their members to defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, order defence), armed forces should, if necessary, be further mentioned by the inability of the police, the army, otherwise the state,” they added.
They reported that everything was happening according to the method that, based on the rancore of political society and parties, seeks to dress different political ambitions in a civil aspect.
The focus on the civilian nature and association status therefore only serves to avoid legal traps from the registration of these associations in the court but also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases risk compared to neighborhood relationships.
“In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk, and ultranationalist political actors in some border countries wish to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This influences the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the constitution of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, political risks have increased across the entire region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard, for example, resembles the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union in August 2007.
The many Roms disturbances that broke out in a neighborhood of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) are the cause of the constitution of the Bulgarian guard.
Taking advantage of these events, the BNU decided to constitute a guard, saying the organization's goal is "national self-defense."
