In Hungary, the law exactly defines the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
Parties are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious feasts or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends, and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter more so that awakening people can rest quietly.
In one year, we have all eleven feasts marked in red.
March 15 is a national celebration, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, as well as October 23, which is the commemorative day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1 is the labour party, and on November 1 and 2 we remember members of our family and deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious feasts rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases or there is only a working day left before or after the celebration marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Labour Minister has decided in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the feasts.
The law extends to all employers and their employees, officials and people working in public service.
It does not, however, apply to services societies, institutions turning without interruption and in service, by their vocation, and also for the rest days.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end-of-year holidays: from December 24, life almost ends throughout the country because, according to experiences, most people do moreover overtime or take vacation that they saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year’s Day home.
